{"continue":{"rvcontinue":"20161224070651|756441159","continue":"||"},"warnings":{"main":{"*":"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application."},"revisions":{"*":"Because \"rvslots\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used."}},"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"David_Price_(American_politician)","to":"David Price (American politician)"}],"pages":{"706615":{"pageid":706615,"ns":0,"title":"David Price (American politician)","revisions":[{"timestamp":"2016-12-24T10:16:57Z","contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{pp-pc1}}\n{{Infobox Congressman\n|birth_name=David Eugene Price\n| name = David Price\n| image = David Price, official Congressional photo portrait.JPG\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1940|08|17}}\n| birth_place = [[Erwin, Tennessee]], United States\n| alma_mater= [[Mars Hill College]], [[University of North Carolina]], [[Yale University]]\n| residence= [[Chapel Hill, North Carolina]]\n| occupation= College Professor\n| state = [[North Carolina]]\n| district = [[North Carolina's 4th congressional district|4th]]\n| term_start = January 3, 1997\n| term_end =\n| preceded = [[Fred Heineman]]\n| succeeded=\n| term_start2=January 3, 1987\n| term_end2=January 3, 1995\n| preceded2=[[Bill Cobey]]\n| succeeded2= [[Fred Heineman]]\n| party = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| spouse = Lisa Price\n| children = Karen Price<br>Michael Price\n| religion = [[Baptist]]\n}}\n\n'''David Eugene Price''' (born August 17, 1940) is a [[professor]] and the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|NC|4}}, serving since 1997 and previously from 1987 to 1995. He is a member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]]. The district includes portions of, among other cities, [[Burlington, North Carolina|Burlington]], [[Fayetteville, North Carolina|Fayetteville]], [[Raleigh, North Carolina|Raleigh]], [[Durham, North Carolina|Durham]], and all of [[Chapel Hill, North Carolina|Chapel Hill]].\n\n==Early life, education, and academic career==\nBorn in [[Erwin, Tennessee]], Price attended [[Mars Hill College]] in [[Mars Hill, North Carolina]] when it was a [[junior college]].<ref name=\"newsobserver\">{{cite news\n  | title = Dogged Price does homework, pursues goals\n  | work = Raleigh News and Observer\n  | date = 1994-10-29\n  | url =\n  | accessdate = 2008-07-03 }}</ref> He later transferred to the [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]], after winning a scholarship, and became a member of [[The Dialectic and Philanthropic Societies]]. He earned a degree in 1961.<ref name=\"newsobserver\"/> Originally intent on becoming an engineer,<ref name=\"newsobserver\"/> Price continued his education at [[Yale University]] where he received a [[theology]] degree (1964) and a Ph.D. in [[political science]] (1969).<ref name=\"about-david\">{{cite web\n  | title = About David\n  | work = [[United States House of Representatives]]\n  | url = http://price.house.gov/about-david\n  | accessdate = 2013-10-23 }}</ref>\n\nHe served as an aide to [[Alaska]] Senator [[Bob Bartlett]] from 1963 to 1967 and then entered [[academia]], working as a [[political science]] and [[public policy]] professor at [[Duke University]] from 1973 until his first campaign for Congress in 1986.<ref name=\"about-david\"/> He also served as a Duke professor during 1995 and 1996, when he was not in Congress.<ref name=\"about-david\"/>\n\nPrice worked for the [[North Carolina Democratic Party]] from 1979 to 1984.<ref name=\"about-david\"/> Price has written a political science textbook entitled ''The Congressional Experience'', from the perspective of a candidate for office, and then, a member of Congress.\n\nPrice also served as executive director and then state chair for the North Carolina Democratic Party prior to being elected to Congress.<ref name=\"newsobserver\"/>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\n;1986-1992\nPrice first entered Congress in 1987 after defeating one-term Republican U.S. Congressman [[Bill Cobey]] 56%-44%.<ref name=\"about-david\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=36363 |title=NC District 4 Race - Nov 04, 1986 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2012-02-10}}</ref> Price won re-election in 1988 and 1990 with 58%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=37714 |title=NC District 4 Race - Nov 08, 1988 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2012-02-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=34408 |title=NC District 4 Race - Nov 06, 1990 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2012-02-10}}</ref> In 1992, he won re-election with 65%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=28253 |title=NC District 4 Race - Nov 03, 1992 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2012-02-10}}</ref>\n\n;1994\nIn 1994, he was narrowly defeated by [[United States Republican Party|Republican]] challenger and former [[Raleigh, North Carolina|Raleigh]] police chief [[Fred Heineman]],  who won by a margin of less than 1%<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=28958 |title=NC District 4 Race - Nov 08, 1994 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2012-02-10}}</ref> during the [[Republican Revolution]], in part to lower-than-expected turnout in the Democratic stronghold of [[Orange County, North Carolina|Orange County]]{{Citation needed|date=July 2008}} (home to Chapel Hill), but despite the fact that heavily Republican [[Randolph County, North Carolina|Randolph County]] had been eliminated from the Fourth District during redistricting prior to that election year.<ref name=\"newsobserver\"/>\n\n;1996\nIn 1996, Price defeated Heineman in a rematch 54%-44%.<ref>{{cite web|title=4th Congressional District|url=http://www.app.sboe.state.nc.us/NCSBE/Elec/Results/PastElect/results9/ushouse.htm|work=US House of Representatives election results|publisher=NC State Board of Elections.|accessdate=20 November 2011}}</ref> He was helped in part by voters who were not happy with the lack of progress made by the freshman class on the goals of the [[Contract with America]].<ref>[http://online.wsj.com/public/article/SB116251835022712110-pJlH0UbKjEJxPOgJSQGH_KAvL4o_20061110.html?mod=blogs Wall Street Journal - Republican Rebels of '94 Now Face Their Own Revolt]</ref>\n\n;1998-2006\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in North Carolina, 2006#District 4}}\nThe district has since reverted to form, and Price won re-election by wide margins in 1998 (57%), 2000 (62%), 2002 (61%), 2004 (64%), and 2006 (65%).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/CandidateDetail.html?CandidateID=1398 |title=Candidate - David E. Price |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2012-02-10}}</ref>\n\n;2008\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in North Carolina, 2008#District 4}}\nPrice's opponent in the 2008 election was Republican [[B.J. Lawson]]. Lawson was called the most formidable opposition Price has faced since he was defeated by Heineman in 1994.<ref name=\"indy weekly\">\n{{cite news\n| last = Sorg\n| first = Lisa\n| title = B.J. Lawson, The Hybrid Candidate\n| work = Independent Weekly\n| date = 2008-10-15\n| url = http://www.indyweek.com/gyrobase/Content?oid=oid%3A266929\n| accessdate = 2008-10-21 }}</ref> For example, he ran television ads, which Price's opponents hadn't done in at least a decade.<ref name=\"newsobserver3\">\n{{cite news\n |last=Teague Beckwith \n |first=Ryan \n |title=Lawson airing ads against Price \n |work=Raleigh News and Observer \n |date=2008-10-16 \n |url=http://projects.newsobserver.com/under_the_dome/lawson_airing_ads_against_price \n |accessdate=2008-10-21 \n |deadurl=yes \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081023202719/http://projects.newsobserver.com/under_the_dome/lawson_airing_ads_against_price \n |archivedate=2008-10-23 \n |df= \n}}</ref> Despite increased efforts and expenditures by his Republican opponent, Price still defeated Lawson 63% to 37%.<ref name=\"n&o4\">\n{{cite news\n |title=Lawson won't seek rematch with Price \n |work=Raleigh News and Observer \n |date=2009-08-06 \n |url=http://www.newsobserver.com/politics/story/41220.html \n}}{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n;2010 \n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in North Carolina, 2010#District 4}}\nOn September 8, 2010, Price launched his reelection campaign. Price defeated Lawson in a rematch 56% to 44%.<ref name=\"daily tarheel\">\n{{cite news\n| last = Kern\n| first = Eliza\n| title = David Price defeats B.J. Lawson in {{sic|hide=y|closely|-}}contested election for House\n| work = The Daily Tar Heel\n| date = 2010-11-03\n| url = http://www.dailytarheel.com/index.php/article/2010/11/price_defeats_lawson_in_closelycontested_election_for_house\n| accessdate = 2010-11-03 }}</ref>\n\n;2012\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in North Carolina, 2012#District 4}}\nPrice defeated Republican nominee and businessman Tim D'Annunzio.\n\n===Tenure===\n[[File:David Price NC Congressman 1992.jpg|thumbnail|left|David Price in 1992]]\nHe was an early opponent of the [[Iraq War of 2003]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://price.house.gov/list/speech/nc04_price/100902.shtml|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080528203815/http://price.house.gov/list/speech/nc04_price/100902.shtml|archivedate=23 August 2013|title=An Alternative to the Iraq War Resolution|author=David Price|publisher=[[United States House of Representatives]]|date=9 October 2002}}</ref> and has sponsored a bill to bring the conduct of [[private military companies]] working in Iraq under legal jurisdiction of the United States.<ref>{{cite news|title=House Bill Would Allow Prosecution of Contractors|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2007/10/04/washington/05cong.html|author=David M. Herszenhorn|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=October 4, 2007}}</ref>  He has also introduced legislation to prohibit contractors from performing interrogations of prisoners in the custody of intelligence agencies.<ref>{{cite news|title=Interrogation for Profit|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2008/06/12/opinion/12thu1.html|work=The New York Times|date=June 12, 2008}}</ref>\n\nAs chairman of the 2008 House subcommittee responsible for determining the budget for the [[Department of Homeland Security]], Price was seeking to focus immigration enforcement efforts on criminal convicts.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dems raise stakes on immigration|url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0608/11125.html|work=[[Politico]]|author= David Rogers|date= June 17, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Dems: ICE should focus on criminals, not workers |url=http://www.newsobserver.com/politics/story/1119495.html |work=[[The News & Observer]] |author=Barbara Barrett |date=June 25, 2008 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080715235048/http://www.newsobserver.com:80/politics/story/1119495.html |archivedate=2008-07-15 |df= }}</ref>\n\nPrice authored a provision of the [[Taxpayer Relief Act of 1997]] which made the interest on student loans tax deductible,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/bdquery/z?d105:HR02014:@@@D&summ2=m&%7cTOM:/bss/d105query.html |title=Bill Summary & Status - 105th Congress (1997 - 1998) - H.R.2014 - CRS Summary - THOMAS (Library of Congress) |publisher=Thomas.loc.gov |date= |accessdate=2012-02-10}}</ref> and legislation creating the Advanced Technological Education program at the [[National Science Foundation]], which provides grants for high-tech education in community colleges and was enacted in 1993.<ref>[http://price.house.gov/congress/legislation.shtml Price website: My Work in Congress: Legislative Accomplishments]</ref>\nPrice voted for the [[Emergency Economic Stabilization Act of 2008]],<ref name=\"newsobserver4\">\n\n{{cite news\n |last=Teague Beckwith \n |first=Ryan \n |title=Roll call on bailout bill \n |work=Raleigh News and Observer \n |date=2008-10-03 \n |url=http://projects.newsobserver.com/under_the_dome/roll_call_on_bailout_bill \n |accessdate=2008-10-21 \n |deadurl=yes \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081023195456/http://projects.newsobserver.com/under_the_dome/roll_call_on_bailout_bill \n |archivedate=2008-10-23 \n |df= \n}}</ref> reasoning that \"the harmful effects of the credit crisis on all North Carolinians were too great for the federal government to sit on the sidelines.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://price.house.gov/list/press/nc04_price/MESSAGEFROMCONGRESSMANPRICEONFINANCIALCRISIS.shtml|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081013223645/http://price.house.gov/list/press/nc04_price/MESSAGEFROMCONGRESSMANPRICEONFINANCIALCRISIS.shtml|archivedate=23 August 2013|title=MESSAGE FROM CONGRESSMAN DAVID PRICE ON FINANCIAL CRISIS|author=David Price|publisher=[[United States House of Representatives]]|date=29 September 2008}}</ref> and for \"[defending] critical emergency management and homeland security priorities\" was honored with an award by the association of state [[emergency management|emergency managers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nemaweb.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=391&Itemid=439 |title=NEMA Timeline |publisher=Nemaweb.org |date= |accessdate=2013-10-23}}</ref> In December 2009, he voted for the [[Dodd\u2013Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act|Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act]], which enacted more stringent regulations on the financial industry in order to protect consumers and taxpayers from another financial crisis.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2009/roll968.xml |title=Final Vote Results For Roll Call 968 |publisher=United States House of Representative |date=11 December 2009 |accessdate=2013-10-23}}</ref>\n\nPrice is the author of legislation to reform the [[public financing]] system for presidential campaigns.<ref>{{cite news|title=Point of View: Public financing's cleansing power |url=http://www.newsobserver.com/opinion/columns/story/1136500.html |work=The News & Observer |author=Chase Foster |date=July 10, 2008 }}{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nPrice has opposed [[concentration of media ownership]]. He worked on legislative initiatives to roll back the FCC's 2003 rules <ref>{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/public-statement/214213/press-release-price-leads-effort-to-hold-fcc-accountable-on-media-ownership-rules#.UvEMpPuoT3A|title=Press Release - Price Leads Effort to Hold FCC Accountable on Media Ownership Rules|author= David Price|date=2006-09-21|accessdate=2014-02-04}}</ref> and co-sponsored an (unsuccessful) bill to overturn another 2008 FCC approval of media consolidation <ref>{{cite web|url=http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/query/z?c110:S.J.RES.28:|title=Bill Text Versions 110th Congress (2007-2008) S.J.RES.28|date=2008|accessdate=2014-02-04}}</ref> Price voted for the 2006 \"Markey amendment\" to establish [[net neutrality in the United States|network neutrality]] in the Communication Act of 1934 <ref>{{cite web|url=http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/bdquery/z?d109:HZ00987:|title=Bill Summary & Status109th Congress (2005 - 2006)H.AMDT.987 to H.R.5252 |year=2006|publisher=[[THOMAS|Thomas]]|accessdate=2013-10-23}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Price voted against the amendment to the [[Patriot Act]] that would have eliminated Section 215 and curtailed the National Security Agency's controversial data collection program.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/113-2013/h412|title=H.Amdt. 413 (Amash) to H.R. 2397|year=2013|publisher=[[GovTrack]]|accessdate=2013-10-23}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Appropriations|Committee on Appropriations]]'''\n**[[United States House Appropriations Subcommittee on Homeland Security|Subcommittee on Homeland Security]] \n**[[United States House Appropriations Subcommittee on the Legislative Branch|Subcommittee on the Legislative Branch]]\n**[[United States House Appropriations Subcommittee on Transportation, Housing and Urban Development, and Related Agencies|Subcommittee on Transportation, Housing and Urban Development, and Related Agencies]] (Ranking Member)\n\n===Caucus memberships===\n*Congressional Humanities Caucus (Co-Chair)\n*House Democracy Partnership\n*[[United States Congressional International Conservation Caucus|International Conservation Caucus]]\n*National Service Caucus (Co-Chair)\n*Congressional Arts Caucus\n\nPrice also serves as Chairman of the House Democracy Assistance Commission, which works through peer-to-peer partnerships with emerging democratic legislatures to assist in the development of the fundamental building blocks of legislative government.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hdac.house.gov/about.shtml |title=About the Commission |publisher=House Democracy Assistance Commission |date= |accessdate=2013-10-23}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nPrice married his wife, Lisa Kanwit, in 1968. They were longtime Democratic Party activists together,<ref name=\"newsobserver\"/> and they have two children: Karen, a filmmaker; and Michael, a professor of Evolutionary Psychology at [[Brunel University]] in London.<ref name=\"about-david\"/> They have two grandchildren, Charles Albert, born in 2006, and Margaret Elizabeth, born in 2009.<ref name=\"about-david\"/> Today, Price resides in [[Chapel Hill, North Carolina|Chapel Hill]]<ref name=\"newsobserver\"/> and is a member of the Binkley Memorial Baptist Church.\n\nPrice appeared as a contestant on the nighttime version of the [[CBS]] [[game show]] [[Password (game show)|Password]], which aired on November 28, 1963, while he was a graduate student at Yale.  His celebrity partner was Gloria Stewart, wife of [[James Stewart]], and they lost to [[James Stewart]] and his contestant partner.  Price won a consolation prize of $50.{{Citation needed|date=July 2011}}\n\nPrice received the 2011 [[John Tyler Caldwell]] Award for the Humanities from the [http://www.nchumanities.org North Carolina Humanities Council].\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsobserver.com/2011/07/17/1349599/legacy-to-be-highway-not-fundraising.html |title=Dome: Legacy to be highway, not fundraising issue - Under the Dome |publisher=NewsObserver.com |date=2011-07-17 |accessdate=2012-02-10 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110918135524/http://www.newsobserver.com:80/2011/07/17/1349599/legacy-to-be-highway-not-fundraising.html |archivedate=2011-09-18 |df= }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Government of the United States/Legislative branch|North Carolina}}\n*[[North Carolina Democratic Party]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikisource author}}\n*[http://www.house.gov/price/ Congressman David Price] official U.S. House site\n*[http://www.priceforcongress.com Price for Congress] \n*{{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/North_Carolina/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/David_Price_%5BD-4%5D|David Price}}\n{{CongLinks | congbio = p000523 | ballot = David_Price | nndb = 108/000039988 | votesmart = 119 | govtrack = 400326 | opencong = 400326 | rollcall = 292 | politifact = | fec = H6NC04037 | opensecrets = N00002260 | assets = david-price | legistorm = 429/Rep_David_Eugene_Price.html | followthemoney = | ontheissues = NC/David_Eugene_Price.htm | congress = david-price/930 | worldcat = | cspan = 6748 | imdb = | bloomberg = | nyt = | washpo = gIQAd3ZCAP }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{USRepSuccessionBox |\n  state=North Carolina|\n  district=4 |\n  before=[[Bill Cobey]] |\n  after=[[